<div id="review_48541694" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/48541694" />
    <a title="Lacey N." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/646726-lacey-n"><img alt="Lacey N." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1248270708p2/646726.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/48541694?book_show_action=true">Mar 07, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lacey N." class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lacey N." href="/user/show/646726-lacey-n">Lacey N.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781570628726" href="/book/show/871520.The_Wisdom_of_No_Escape">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer48541694" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer334607265696776507">I picked Pema Chodron&apos;s book after I saw it laying on a friend&apos;s coffee table, intrigued but not completely convinced. I expected a self-helpy and precious book that I would drop after reading the first few pages. I was surprised, however, when Chodron&apos;s clear, intellectual prose brought me to a wholly unexpected place. Buddhism is often overly-cerebral and vague to me, with metaphorical stories I can never quite grasp. Chodron, a Buddhist nun, writes from the Buddhist perspective with a recogni</span>
  <span id="freeText334607265696776507" style="display:none">I picked Pema Chodron's book after I saw it laying on a friend's coffee table, intrigued but not completely convinced. I expected a self-helpy and precious book that I would drop after reading the first few pages. I was surprised, however, when Chodron's clear, intellectual prose brought me to a wholly unexpected place. Buddhism is often overly-cerebral and vague to me, with metaphorical stories I can never quite grasp. Chodron, a Buddhist nun, writes from the Buddhist perspective with a recognition that her audience most likely wasn't raised on the eight-fold path. She breaks down the essential concepts behind the various sutras without losing the greater philosophical tenents. She encourages us to be "warriors" on our paths to becoming more awake and alive, to engage with our fears--of success, of failure, of intimacy--without running away, with loving-kindess to ourselves. As someone whose harshest critic is usually myself, I found comfort in Chodron's discriptions of loving kindness. Recommended for anyone craving intellectual self-reflection.</span>
  <a data-text-id="334607265696776507" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


